    <center><table class="itemDisplayTable">
<tr><td class="metadataFieldLabel">Title:&nbsp;</td><td class="metadataFieldValue">Approaches for Managing Data Transactions in Manet</td></tr>
<tr><td class="metadataFieldLabel">Authors:&nbsp;</td><td class="metadataFieldValue">Murali.M</td></tr>
<tr><td class="metadataFieldLabel">Keywords:&nbsp;</td><td class="metadataFieldValue">Managing Data Transactions</td></tr>
<tr><td class="metadataFieldLabel">Issue Date:&nbsp;</td><td class="metadataFieldValue">Nov-2013 </td></tr>
<tr><td class="metadataFieldLabel">Publisher:&nbsp;</td><td class="metadataFieldValue">SRM University</td></tr>
<tr><td class="metadataFieldLabel">Series/Report no.:&nbsp;</td><td class="metadataFieldValue">T0118</td></tr>
<tr><td class="metadataFieldLabel">Abstract:&nbsp;</td><td class="metadataFieldValue">This research work considers the data access to various servers and finding the routes to other mobile hosts in a distributed mobile network with special concentration on mobile host migration, energy limitation, network disconnection and transaction timings. To access different data sources from wireless environment a mobile agent methodology is employed. A mobile agent is a software program that migrates from one node to another where the data is located instead of transmitting data across the network. The base station has an embedded Queuing System. Query from any mobile Unit, assumed to be coming in the form of packets out of the respective Transmitter terminal Tx, is served either using priority mode or as First-come-First Served basis. Output of the queuing system is connected to the coordinator agent which sends the query to all Search Agents in parallel. The Interface Selector, of that Search Agent, which recognizes the query to the associated database will take over for further action. Once data against the query is retrieved, it is routed to the base station in the reverse path. At the output of the Base Station is located a DeMultiplexer, that routes the query via Receiver Port (Rx) of the Mobile Unit which demanded the query. The performance of the system depends mainly on the effectiveness of the Queuing system
The modified approach is also described to provide a solution for real-time data transfer with bandwidth reservation. In this thesis, modified MAC algorithm is used, since it is adaptive in nature and change its behaviour according to load variations. Normally waiting time after collision increases exponentially; this means the
contention window increases by two times of the present one; but in the proposed method it is proved that the contention window increases slowly. Collision and loss of packets are the major problems in wireless networks compared to wired networks. Then how much time should be spent for waiting when the carrier is busy, waiting after collision or loss of packets etc. are other critical issues in wireless domain. The approach is modified to overcome these issues.
The data may be available in the mobile nodes or in the fixed network. To access the cached data, Modified Ad hoc On-Demand Distance Vector (M-AODV) protocol is used in MANET. In this protocol energy aware route discovery method is adopted. The node sends the request by sending the message in the network. All other nodes will receive the request and check the availability of the data in their cache area. Then the nodes will reply to the requested node, if the data is available with them. The requested node will consider the first reply to access the data using M-AODV</td></tr>
<tr><td class="metadataFieldLabel">URI:&nbsp;</td><td class="metadataFieldValue"><a href="http://hdl.handle.net/123456789/13722">http://hdl.handle.net/123456789/13722</a></td></tr>
<tr><td class="metadataFieldLabel">Appears in Collections:</td><td class="metadataFieldValue"><a href="/dspace/handle/123456789/6855">Ph.D - Thesis  </a><br/></td></tr>
</table></center><br/>
